   <mods:abstract>John Jay says that William's offer to come immediately if his father has
            taken the fever is not founded on good judgment. If our duty bids us rush into danger we
            should do so cheerfully, acting in obedience to divine Providence. But we violate our
            duty when we tempt Providence by running into danger unnecessarily. Jay's heart and
            conscience will not permit him to subject William to the danger of taking the fever. If
            Jay becomes ill, he will send for William immediately.</mods:abstract>
